\f0\fs24 \cf0 This thing is set up as a tree. Each item on the tree is a list, except for Traits. When you click 
\b Generate
\b0 , the program goes through every item on the top menu and either picks option at random or adds one thing for each of them, depending on what it is. \
\
\

\b Template
\b0 : A type of NPC (
\i Human
\i0 ). \
	Templates put every Aspect and one nested Template onto your NPC.\

\b Aspect
\b0 : A bundle of lists (
\i Human Full Name
\i0 ).\
	 Aspects put one random item onto your NPC.\
\

\b List
\b0 : A list of options (
\i American Human First Name
\i0 ). \
	Lists put one random Trait into that slot for your NPC.\

\b Trait
\b0 : An item on a list (
\i John
\i0 ). \
	Traits go straight onto the final NPC, but can have random elements.\
\
The tops of the tree must be templates. Templates and Aspects can hold any item. Lists can only hold Traits and Traits can't hold anything, although they can have random elements.\
\
Templates can be inside each other to create more specific version of itself. (
\i Human
\i0  contains 
\i American Human
\i0 ). The nested Template only needs to contain things that are being replaced or added. (
\i American Human
\i0  has 
\i Home State
\i0  and 
\i American First Name
\i0  (replacing 
\i Human First Name
\i0 ), but not 
\i Personality
\i0  because 
\i Human
\i0  already has 
\i Personality
\i0 .)\
	
\fs22 Note that having specific types of Human means that you will never get a basic human.
\fs18  Unless you left click within Human (while viewing its contents) and select "Allow as Complete". This adds a "<" to the Template which just means that you can sometimes get a basic Human. You can undo that by deleting the "<".
